Multiple Regression

In R, run multiple regressions with lm (short for linear model):

lm(mpg ~ wt + cyl, data=mtcars)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = mpg ~ wt + cyl, data = mtcars)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)           wt          cyl  
##      39.686       -3.191       -1.508

More detailed regression results

  1. Pass the results from lm() to summary() for more detailed information:
lm(mpg ~ wt + cyl, data=mtcars) %>%
  summary()
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = mpg ~ wt + cyl, data = mtcars)
##

For better formatting of the results (pretty print), we can use the texreg package:

## Install and load texreg package
install.packages("texreg")
library(texreg)

# Pretty print regression results on screen
lm(mpg ~ wt + cyl, data=mtcars) %>%
  screenreg()
## 
## ======================
##              Model 1  
## ----------------------
## (Intercept)  39.69 ***
##              (1.71)   
## wt           -3.19 ***
##              (0.76)   
## cyl          -1.51 ** 
##              (0.41)   
## ----------------------
## R^2           0.83    
## Adj. R^2      0.82    
## Num. obs.    32       
## RMSE          2.57    
## ======================
## *** p < 0.001, ** p < 0.01, * p < 0.05
# Save regression results to a html file
lm(mpg ~ wt + cyl, data=mtcars) %>%
  htmlreg(file="output/lm_mpg-wt+cyl.html")
  1. Confidence interval of coefficients
lm(mpg ~ wt + cyl, data=mtcars) %>%
  confint()
##                 2.5 %     97.5 %
## (Intercept) 36.178725 43.1937976
## wt          -4.739020 -1.6429245
## cyl         -2.355928 -0.6596622

Visualize regression results

ggplot(mtcars, aes(x=wt, y=mpg)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)

ggplot(mtcars, aes(x=cyl, y=mpg)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)

betas <- lm(mpg ~ wt + cyl, data=mtcars) %>% summary() %>% coef()
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x=wt, y=mpg)) + geom_point() +
  geom_abline(aes(slope=betas["wt", "Estimate"], intercept=betas["(Intercept)", "Estimate"]))

ggplot(mtcars, aes(x=cyl, y=mpg)) + geom_point() +
  geom_abline(aes(slope=betas["cyl", "Estimate"], intercept=betas["(Intercept)", "Estimate"]))

Hypothesis testing of nested models

## Install and load ggfortify package

lm_mpg_wt <- lm(mpg ~ wt, data=mtcars)
lm_mpg_wt.cyl <- lm(mpg ~ wt + cyl, data=mtcars)

anova(lm_mpg_wt, lm_mpg_wt.cyl)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Model 1: mpg ~ wt
## Model 2: mpg ~ wt + cyl
##   Res.Df    RSS Df Sum of Sq     F   Pr(>F)   
## 1     30 278.32                               
## 2     29 191.17  1     87.15 13.22 0.001064 **
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Tasks

  1. Create a new RStudio project and create directory structure following the recommendation in Project Management With RStudio;
  2. Select a dataset from the [Tools and Datasets] section of the course website or use your own dataset, save the dataset in the data folder of your project;
  3. Famarlize yourself with your dataset with the data document;
  4. Create a script that imports your dataset into R and explores it with descriptive statistics and/or visulization;
  5. Choose a dependent variable and a couple of independent variables and run regression models;
  6. Create regression plots (scatter plot superimposed with a regression line) & diagnostic plots.
